Buy #Bitcoin

I am willing to be misunderstood for long periods of time.

Cherish this period.

This is one of those times where #Bitcoin bulls look understood,

but a lot more is yet to come.

It holds a unique charm you'll look back on fondly.

Life is exceedingly brief.

-Don't squander it.

-Extract every bit of joy and meaning you desire from it.

This is why I am in the Bitcoin ecosystem.

This decade is set to be monumental.

Statistically speaking,

most of us are among the most fortunate individuals ever to have existed.

That doesn't mean we're devoid of challenges.

Everyone faces difficulties.

It's vital to maintain a broader perspective on just how privileged we are.

Practice gratitude, buy Bitcoin, study and chill.

Time is the most important concept to grasp.

Time is our scarcest resource.

Impatience for victory will guarantee defeat,

Time will always be more valuable than money.

üí° Runes Standard on Bitcoin, Explained

TL;DR: Runes aims to provide a simple, Bitcoin-native token system with a unique issuance model and efficient on-chain footprint ‚Äî its UTXO (unspent transaction output) approach differing from standards like BRC-20.

While BRC-20 is the most widely used token standard native to Bitcoin, other metaprotocols are catching up ‚Äî offering new utilities, overcoming existing limitations etc.

üìà Runes is one such competitor.

Runes is a new fungible token protocol proposed by Casey Rodarmor, the creator of Ordinals.

Simply put, it is a UTXO-based system that aims for:

‚Üí A smooth UX for Bitcoin users in creating and transferring tokens.
‚Üí A smaller on-chain footprint with smart UTXO management.

With Runes, token balances live inside UTXOs. A single UTXO can hold any amount of any number of Runes tokens.

üí° Issuing mechanism for Runes

‚Üí Rather than tying balances to addresses, Runes tokens get issued directly into a UTXO in the issuance transaction. This sets the initial supply, ticker symbol, and number of decimal places.
‚Üí From there, the UTXO holding the tokens can be split up and reorganized through regular transfers.
‚Üí The issuer can send any quantity of their issued Runes to any number of recipients by creating outputs assigned to the token using the protocol message format.

üí° Differences from BRC-20

‚Üí A key difference is that Runes aligns closer to Bitcoin's native UTXO model, instead of something purposely bolted on like BRC-20.
‚Üí Transfers rely on compact OP_RETURN messages rather than bespoke transaction types. This makes Runes more efficient with a smaller on-chain footprint.
‚Üí The issuance mechanism is also more transparent, defined by a specific message format.
‚Üí Another advantage is that Runes is inherently compatible with Lightning, unlocking new possibilities.

üß™ Ordiswap is the first native AMM on Bitcoin L1, supporting direct $BTC/BRC-20 swaps.

ü§ù Our infrastructure allows us to support all major token standards ‚Äî SRC-20, CBRC-20, DRC-20, Runes etc.

üß° Runes are one that we are now specifically looking into, and we cannot be more excited about the potential of the BTC DeFi ecosystem in the coming months!

‚Üí a smaller on-chain footprint with smart utxo management.

with runes, token balances live inside utxos. a single utxo can hold any amount of any number of runes tokens.

üí° issuing mechanism for runes

‚Üí rather than tying balances to addresses, runes tokens get issued directly into a utxo in the issuance transaction. this sets the initial supply, ticker symbol, and number of decimal places.
‚Üí from there, the utxo holding the tokens can be split up and reorganized through regular transfers.
‚Üí the issuer can send any quantity of their issued runes to any number of recipients by creating outputs assigned to the token using the protocol message format.

üí° differences from brc-20

‚Üí a key difference is that runes aligns closer to bitcoin's native utxo model, instead of something purposely bolted on like brc-20.
‚Üí transfers rely on compact op_return messages rather than bespoke transaction types. this makes runes more efficient with a smaller on-chain footprint.
‚Üí the issuance mechanism is also more transparent, defined by a specific message format.
‚Üí another advantage is that runes is inherently compatible with lightning, unlocking new possibilities.

üß™ ordiswap is the first native amm on bitcoin l1, supporting direct $btc/brc-20 swaps.

ü§ù our infrastructure allows us to support all major token standards ‚Äî src-20, cbrc-20, drc-20, runes etc.

üß° runes are one that we are now specifically looking into, and we cannot be more excited about the potential of the btc defi ecosystem in the coming months!

üèõ Ordibank is building the Compound Finance on native Bitcoin, paving the way to unlock billions in idle liquidity in $BTC, BRC-20s and Atomicals... but there are also other standards like SRC-20s, CBRC-20s, Runes and beyond.

Each token standard has its own unique utility and novelty, opening up multiple possibilities for DeFi on Bitcoin ‚ö°Ô∏è

ü§ù We are excited to be exploring their support, with the goal to provide our users with the most DeFi opportunities possible on #BTC's native layer.

A quick overview of different token standards (with details from @TheSpartanGroup Bitcoin research):

üìú BRC-20

In early 2023, DOMO unveiled BRC-20, an experimental Bitcoin token standard inspired by Ethereum's ERC-20.

ü™ô It utilized Ordinal inscriptions and JSON data to create fungible tokens tailored for Bitcoin's ecosystem, though with constrained capabilities.

$ORDI, the inaugural BRC-20 token, attained a market capitalization surpassing $1 billion by May 2023, ranking among the top cryptocurrencies.

üìú BRC-721E

Collaboratively developed by Bitcoin Miladys, Ordinals Market, and Xverse, BRC-721E emerged as an experimental standard akin to Ethereum's ERC-721 for non-fungible tokens (NFTs).

üñºÔ∏è Initially, it enabled bridging Ethereum NFTs to Bitcoin, inscribing a simplified version with a link to the original and airdrop functionality.

üìú CY[BORD] (CBRC-20)

Imagine BRC-20 with a twist: more budget-friendly and user-friendly indexing.

üìà Key variances:

‚Ä¢ Reduced costs for token setup, creation, and movement
‚Ä¢ Streamlined indexing processes

üìú ORC-20

ORC-20 aimed to enhance BRC-20 with backward compatibility, flexible naming, and UTXO integration to prevent double-spending.

Meanwhile, ORC-CASH, based on the Ordinals Protocol, was designed as a streamlined ORC-20 variant optimized for UTXO security.

üìú RUNES

RUNES, an experimental fungible token protocol intended as a BRC-20 alternative.

Unlike BRC-20, RUNES avoided off-chain data and native tokens, instead utilizing UTXOs and specific script conditions for transaction identification.

üìú SRC-20

My crypto journey began in 2009 with the controversial documentary "Zeitgeist." Despite my economic background, it was then when I truly understood our financial system's flaws. Now, with #Bitcoin nearing its all-time highs, I'm eager to share why I chose BTC. Let‚Äôs dive in. üëá

The segment "Don't Mind The Men Behind The Curtain" from "Zeitgeist" takes a critical look at the global financial system with a spotlight on the U.S. Federal Reserve. It reveals how the Federal Reserve was established in 1913, not as a governmental body but as a private coalition of banks. The film exposes a significant concern: the Federal Reserve, in spite of its governmental-sounding name, acts as a banking cartel with the unchecked ability to print money, operating without direct government oversight. This structure concentrates power in the hands of a few wealthy individuals and institutions.

I understood for the first time that money in the modern economy is created out of debt. When banks issue loans, new money is literally created through the borrowers' promises to pay back the borrowed sums with interest. This system, according to "Zeitgeist," perpetuates a cycle of debt, because the money to pay back the interest on all the loans does not exist in the system; it can only be sourced from more debt. This leads to an inevitable increase in the money supply, causing inflation and diminishing the purchasing power of the dollar over time.

Moreover, "Zeitgeist" suggests that this debt-based monetary system has far-reaching implications, affecting everything from individual financial well-being to national policy and global economics. It says that this system fuels an endless cycle of boom and bust, enriching the financial elite while the general population struggles with inflation, increasing debt, and economic instability. I realized that the Federal Reserve and the broader banking system have immense influence over government policies, manipulating economies for profit at the expense of societal health and stability.

Bitcoin, introduced in 2009, was a direct response to these systemic flaws. It presented a novel solution: a decentralized currency, free from the control of any bank, government, or central authority. Unlike fiat currencies, Bitcoin is created through mining, which requires computational power to solve complex mathematical problems. This process is predetermined and transparent, ensuring that no single entity can manipulate the currency's value through unchecked money creation.

The blockchain's auditable nature democratizes financial interactions, establishing a system where trust is distributed across its architecture rather than concentrated in singular institutions. The move to direct, person-to-person transactions is part of a bigger idea to make the economy fairer for everyone. It shifts financial control away from a small group of powerful people to the wider population.

Fun fact: Whenever someone tells me Bitcoin is a scam, I can't help but chuckle. The reality is, if the US dollar came with a whitepaper detailing its operations, it would be dismissed as a worthless shitcoin. 

The moment I read the Bitcoin Whitepaper, I became convinced of its superiority over the dollar.

I'm genuinely interested in hearing about your journey. What convinced you of Bitcoin and cryptocurrency's potential?

Everyone, and I mean EVERYONE who says that #Bitcoin is too volatile to be useful as a currency is missing one obvious thing. Well, maybe it's not so obvious, until you hear it. üëá

Every one of the fiat currencies on earth today are the unit of account in their nations. When the medium of exchange is the unit of account, it doesn't fluctuate. It cannot be volatile because everything is priced in it. Goods and services can only fluctuate AGAINST it. 

(This gives people the illusion that the inflation problem is greedy corporations increasing prices, and not the money itself losing value.)

The idea of a medium of exchange which is not also the unit of account is ludicrous when you stop and think about it. It can't work. It wouldn't be "stable" enough for anyone to use as a currency. 

In terms of BTC, it won't be until everything is priced in "sats" or "bits" that #Bitcoin will feel natural to use as a medium of exchange. Prices will still fluctuate against it. But we can expect a gradual DECREASE in prices each year, equivalent to our net productivity gains. Quite the opposite of volatile. This is what stability based on math and truth looks like. üëÜ

I'd always thought of the progression as Store of Value, then Medium of Exchange, and finally, Unit of Account. But, as @saifedean said recently, Bitcoin is like gunpowder. Adopting gun powder wasn't optional for nation states. If they failed to, they were overtaken by nations who did. Like gun powder, Bitcoin is not optional.

I suspect that after the world crowds into #BTC as a Store of Value, it will become the Medium of Exchange AND the Unit of Account all at once. Everywhere. It only makes sense. 

There's a word for this--Hyperbitcoinization. It'll come sooner than we expect. üëÄ
